Looking at the mutation, the change is from `var hasStacks = false` to `var hasStacks = true`. This variable controls whether stack trace functionality is enabled. When `hasStacks` is `true`, the code will try to use stack traces in various places.

The key observable effect: when `hasStacks = true` (mutated), the `Q.longStackSupport` feature will attempt to attach stack traces to deferred promises. More importantly, the `captureLine()` function is called at startup to capture `qStartingLine` and `qFileName`. With `hasStacks = false` (original), `captureLine()` returns `undefined` immediately. With `hasStacks = true` (mutated), it tries to capture actual stack info.

The most reliable observable difference is in the `isInternalFrame` function behavior and how stack traces are filtered. But a more direct observable effect is that with `hasStacks = true`, when `Q.longStackSupport = true`, deferred promises will have a `.stack` property attached.

Let me find a clean way to detect this: with the original (`hasStacks = false`), even with `Q.longStackSupport = true`, the deferred promise will NOT get a `.stack` property (because the condition is `if (Q.longStackSupport && hasStacks)`). With the mutation (`hasStacks = true`), it WILL get a `.stack` property.

